This paper deals with the computational complexity of refuting random instances of CSPs using SDP hierarchies, which is a topic in computational complexity theory. Therefore, cs.CC (Computational Complexity) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also involves the analysis of random instances of CSPs, which is related to probabilistic algorithms and random structures, making cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) a likely sub-category as well. The use of SDP hierarchies also suggests a connection to optimization and approximation algorithms, which falls under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.IT (Information Theory). Finally, the paper involves the analysis of distributions over satisfying assignments, which is related to statistical learning theory, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) a possible sub-category as well.
